	<div id="comment_top_65425665" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65425665" name="comment_link_65425665" href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23708925&amp;cid=65425665" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65425665)" >Exceeding Authorized Access is a crime</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65425665" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65425665); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~laughingskeptic">laughingskeptic</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~laughingskeptic">( 1004414 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65425665"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65425665">And when it comes to every scenario involving their computers, the government has taken the point of view if you weren't authorized to do something on their computer and you did it, then you exceeded authorized access.  <a href="https://www.justice.gov/jm/jm-9-48000-computer-fraud" title="justice.gov">https://www.justice.gov/jm/jm-...</a> [justice.gov] .  There was no way for a cellphone owner to authorize this, so it was unauthorized and therefore a crime.</div>
	</div>

